
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `date` baraye namayesh ya tagheer dadane tarikhe rooz va saat dar system estefade mishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `date`  --> 🗓️ Namayesh tarikhe konooni be soorate pishfarz.
    🔹 `date + "%Y-%m-%d"` --> 📅 Namayesh tarikhe konooni ba format delkhah (year-month-day).
    🔹 `date + "%T"` --> ⌚️ Namayesh saat be soorate hour:minute:second.
    🔹 `date -s "STRING"` --> ⏰ Tagheer dadane saat va tarikh (niaz be dastrasi root).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ date

    🔹 Namayesh tarikhe va saat konooni.

    $ date + "%A, %d %B %Y"

    🔹 Namayesh tarikh ba formati ke rooze hafte, rooz, mah va sal ra neshan midahad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ date + "%Y%m%d-%H%M%S"

    🔹 In dastoor tarikh va saat ra be shekle YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS namayesh midahad, baraye sakhte name file-ha ba zaman munasib ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `date` command is used to display or set the system date and time.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `date`  --> 🗓️ Display the current date and time in the default format.
    🔹 `date + "%Y-%m-%d"` --> 📅 Display the current date in a custom format (year-month-day).
    🔹 `date + "%T"` --> ⌚️ Display the time in hour:minute:second format.
    🔹 `date -s "STRING"` --> ⏰ Set the date and time (requires root access).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ date

    🔹 Display the current date and time.

    $ date + "%A, %d %B %Y"

    🔹 Display the date in a format showing the day of the week, day, month, and year.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ date + "%Y%m%d-%H%M%S"

    🔹 This command displays the date and time as YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS, useful for creating filenames with timestamps.
